1	\chapter{Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups, sheafification and Ext}
2	\label{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafAb}
3	
4	This chapter executes Phase~A steps~2--4 of \texttt{STRATEGY.md} on the topology of opens of an arbitrary topological space, using the \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose} as input. It supplies three pieces of infrastructure that sit immediately upstream of Definition~\ref{def:genus} (the genus of a smooth proper curve):
5	
6	\begin{enumerate}
7	  \item \texttt{HasSheafify} for $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves on $\opens X$ (Phase~A step~2).
8	  \item \texttt{HasExt} on the same sheaf category (Phase~A step~3).
9	  \item Promotion of the structure sheaf $\struct C$ from $\CommRingCat$-valued to $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued, packaging the data on which \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.H} can be evaluated (Phase~A step~4 first half).
10	\end{enumerate}
11	
12	A discovery probe of Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} (logged in \texttt{task\_pending.md}) confirms that all three pieces are constructible directly from existing Mathlib API plus the iteration~004 \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance: no new mathematical content is introduced here, only the typeclass plumbing and one definition. After this chapter lands, the only remaining steps in Phase~A are equipping $H^1(C, \struct C)$ with a $k$-vector-space structure and proving Serre finiteness; both are deferred to subsequent iterations.
13	
14	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and instance here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $H^1(C, \struct C)$ in Definition~\ref{def:genus}.
15	
16	\section{Sheafification of $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves on opens}
17	
18	\begin{theorem}[Sheafification on the topology of opens, $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued]
19	  \label{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
20	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
21	  \leanok
22	  Let $X$ be a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of $X$ has
23	  \[
24	    \mathtt{HasSheafify}(\opens(X), \AddCommGrpCat).
25	  \]
26	\end{theorem}
27	
28	\begin{proof}
29	  \leanok
30	  Mathlib's general sheafification API constructs \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} whenever \lstinline{HasWeakSheafify J A} holds and the resulting sheafification preserves finite limits. For \lstinline{J = Opens.grothendieckTopology X} and \lstinline{A = AddCommGrpCat} both prerequisites are already wired in Mathlib (concrete-category sheafification on a small site, plus exactness of $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheafification on a Noetherian-style topology). The instance is therefore inferable; the prover's task is to establish the universe pinning needed to make \lstinline{infer_instance} succeed.
31	\end{proof}
32	
33	\section{$\Ext$ for sheaves on opens}
34	
35	\begin{theorem}[$\Ext$ on the topology of opens, $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued]
36	  \label{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}
37	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}
38	  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}
39	  \leanok
40	  Let $X$ be a topological space. Then the category $\Sheaf(\opens(X), \AddCommGrpCat)$ has
41	  \[
42	    \mathtt{HasExt.\{u+1\}}\bigl(\Sheaf(\opens(X), \AddCommGrpCat)\bigr).
43	  \]
44	\end{theorem}
45	
46	\begin{proof}
47	  \leanok
48	  $\AddCommGrpCat$ is abelian. The sheaf category $\Sheaf(J, A)$ inherits an abelian structure from an abelian $A$ once \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} holds (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}). Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} produces a \lstinline{HasExt} instance from any abelian category. The universe annotation \lstinline{HasExt.\{u+1\}} matches the unique morphism universe of \lstinline{Sheaf (Opens.gT X) AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}}, which lives at type-universe \lstinline{u+1}; the sheafification API forces this shape.
49	\end{proof}
50	
51	\section{Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups}
52	
53	\begin{definition}[Structure sheaf as a sheaf of abelian groups]
54	  \label{def:Scheme_toAbSheaf}
55	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toAbSheaf}
56	  \uses{thm:HasSheafCompose_forget}
57	  \leanok
58	  Let $C$ be a scheme. The structure sheaf of $C$, viewed as a sheaf of abelian groups on the topology of opens of the underlying topological space of $C$, is
59	  \[
60	    \toAbSheaf(C) \;:=\; (\sheafCompose(\opens(\Csp), F_{\mathrm{forget}})).\mathtt{obj}\;C.\mathtt{sheaf} \;\in\; \Sheaf(\opens(\Csp), \AddCommGrpCat),
61	  \]
62	  where $\Csp$ is the underlying topological space of $C$, $C.\mathtt{sheaf} \in \Sheaf(\opens(\Csp), \CommRingCat)$ is the Mathlib structure sheaf, and $F_{\mathrm{forget}} = \forget_2 \CommRingCat \RingCat \circ \forget_2 \RingCat \AddCommGrpCat$ is the forget composite of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose}.
63	\end{definition}
64	
65	The construction uses \lstinline{CategoryTheory.sheafCompose}, which requires the \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance from Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose}. Functoriality in $C$ is delegated to a future iteration once we need it for naturality of the cohomology long exact sequence.
66	
67	\section{Use in the project}
68	
69	The chain $\HasSheafCompose \to \HasSheafify \to \HasExt \to \toAbSheaf$ unblocks the abelian-group-level definition of $H^n(C, \struct C)$:
70	\[
71	  H^n(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \toAbSheaf(C).\mathtt{H}\,n,
72	\]
73	where \lstinline{Sheaf.H} is the abstract sheaf-cohomology API of Mathlib's \lstinline{Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean}. The result is automatically an \lstinline{AddCommGroup} via \lstinline{Sheaf.instAddCommGroupH}. Only two steps remain inside Phase~A:
74	
75	\begin{itemize}
76	  \item Equip $H^1(C, \struct C)$ with the $k$-module structure inherited from the $k$-algebra structure on $\Gamma(C, \struct C)$ (Phase~A step~5).
77	  \item Establish $\Module.\finrank$ finiteness via Serre's theorem on coherent cohomology of proper $k$-schemes (Phase~A step~6 / "finiteness").
78	\end{itemize}
79	
80	Both are deferred to iterations beyond this chapter.
81	
82	\section{Mathlib gap}
83	
84	Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} carries every constituent piece needed for this chapter:
85	\begin{itemize}
86	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasSheafify} and the small-site / concrete-category sheafification API for $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves on $\opens(X)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}: \lstinline{infer_instance} succeeds for \lstinline{HasSheafify (Opens.grothendieckTopology X) AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}}).
87	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} for any abelian category, and the abelian instance \lstinline{Sheaf.instAbelian} on $\Sheaf(J, \AddCommGrpCat)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}).
88	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.sheafCompose} together with the \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} instance of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose} (closed in iteration~004).
89	  \item The structure sheaf \lstinline{Scheme.sheaf : Sheaf (Opens.grothendieckTopology X.toTopCat) CommRingCat} is built into the Mathlib \lstinline{Scheme} structure.
90	\end{itemize}
91	
92	Nothing is genuinely missing for this chapter; the work is to assemble the typeclass plumbing with universe annotations chosen so that downstream \lstinline{Sheaf.H} consumers can reach the sheaf via \lstinline{infer_instance}.
