\chapter{Sheaves of $k$-modules: sheafification and Ext}
\label{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafModuleK}

This chapter sets up the prerequisites for Phase~A step~5 of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}: equipping $H^1(C, \struct C)$ with a $k$-vector-space structure when $C$ is a scheme over $\Spec k$. The route is through Mathlib's general $\Linear k$ enrichment of $\Sheaf(\opens X, \ModuleCat k)$ together with \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule}, which automatically provides $\Module k$ on $\Ext$ groups in any $\Linear k$ abelian category. The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every instance here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $H^1(C, \struct C)$ in Definition~\ref{def:genus}.

The chapter intentionally does \emph{not} yet construct the $\ModuleCat k$-valued structure sheaf $\toModuleKSheaf C$ (the analogue of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toAbSheaf}); that step requires viewing $\struct C$ as a sheaf of $k$-modules via the structure morphism $C \to \Spec k$, which is the substantial technical work for Phase~A step~5 main and is deferred to a subsequent iteration. The two instances below are the typeclass plumbing that makes the eventual $\toModuleKSheaf$ chain work.

A discovery probe of Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} (logged in \texttt{task\_pending.md}) confirms that all three pieces below — the two instances and the auto-inferable $\Linear k$ enrichment — are already in Mathlib; no new mathematical content is introduced here, only the universe-pinned packaging. After this chapter lands, the typeclass chain \[ \HasSheafify \to \HasExt \to \Linear k \to \mathtt{Ext.instModule} \] is in place; the only remaining step before $H^1(C, \struct C)$ becomes a $k$-vector-space is the iteration~006+ definition of $\toModuleKSheaf$.

\section{Sheafification of $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheaves on opens}

\begin{theorem}[Sheafification on the topology of opens, $\ModuleCat k$-valued]
  \label{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  Let $k$ be a commutative ring and $X$ a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of $X$ has
  \[
    \mathtt{HasSheafify}(\opens(X), \ModuleCat\, k).
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Mathlib's general sheafification API constructs \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} whenever \lstinline{HasWeakSheafify J A} holds and the resulting sheafification preserves finite limits. For \lstinline{J = Opens.grothendieckTopology X} and \lstinline{A = ModuleCat k} both prerequisites are wired in Mathlib (small-site sheafification on a concrete category, plus exactness of $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheafification). The instance is therefore inferable; the prover's task is to reproduce the universe pinning that succeeded for the iter-004 $\AddCommGrpCat$ analogue (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}).
\end{proof}

\section{$\Ext$ for $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheaves on opens}

\begin{theorem}[$\Ext$ on the topology of opens, $\ModuleCat k$-valued]
  \label{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  Let $k$ be a commutative ring and $X$ a topological space. Then the category $\Sheaf(\opens(X), \ModuleCat k)$ has
  \[
    \mathtt{HasExt.\{u+1\}}\bigl(\Sheaf(\opens(X), \ModuleCat k)\bigr).
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  $\ModuleCat k$ is abelian. The sheaf category $\Sheaf(J, A)$ inherits an abelian structure from an abelian $A$ once \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} holds (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}). Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} produces a \lstinline{HasExt} instance from any abelian category. The universe annotation \lstinline{HasExt.\{u+1\}} matches the unique morphism universe of \lstinline{Sheaf (Opens.gT X) (ModuleCat.\{u\} k)}, mirroring the iter-004 $\AddCommGrpCat$ analogue (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}).
\end{proof}

\section{Use in the project}

The chain $\HasSheafify \to \HasExt \to \Linear k \to \mathtt{Ext.instModule}$ unblocks the path from $H^1(C, \struct C)$ as an $\AddCommGroup$ (iter-004) to $H^1(C, \struct C)$ as a $\Module k$ (iter-006+):

\begin{itemize}
  \item Once $\toModuleKSheaf C : \Sheaf(\opens(\Csp), \ModuleCat k)$ is defined (iteration~006+), the cohomology
    \[
      H^n(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \toModuleKSheaf(C).\mathtt{H}\,n
    \]
    is automatically a $\Module k$ via \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule}: the Ext groups in any $\Linear k$ abelian category are themselves $\Module k$.
  \item The forgetful functor $\ModuleCat k \to \AddCommGrpCat$ recovers the iter-004 abelian-group cohomology, so the future $\toModuleKSheaf$ definition will commute with $\toAbSheaf$ on the nose (a forget-and-recover lemma analogous to the iter-005 $\PicardFunctorAb$ forget-compare).
  \item Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, $\finrank_k H^i(C, \mathcal F) < \infty$) remains the deep work to come, but is now expressible inside Mathlib's standard $\Module k$ API.
\end{itemize}

\section{Mathlib gap}

Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} carries every constituent piece needed for this chapter:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasSheafify} and the small-site / concrete-category sheafification API for $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheaves on $\opens(X)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}: \lstinline{infer_instance} succeeds for \lstinline{HasSheafify (Opens.grothendieckTopology X) (ModuleCat.\{u\} k)}).
  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} for any abelian category, and the abelian instance \lstinline{Sheaf.instAbelian} on $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat k)$ via the previous bullet (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}).
  \item The $\Linear k$ enrichment on $\Sheaf(\opens(X), \ModuleCat k)$ is auto-inferable in Mathlib (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code}: \lstinline{infer_instance} succeeds for \lstinline{Linear k (Sheaf (Opens.gT X) (ModuleCat.\{u\} k))}).
  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule} provides $\Module R$ on $\Ext X Y n$ for any $\Linear R$ abelian category (already in Mathlib).
\end{itemize}

Nothing is genuinely missing for this chapter. The genuine missing piece for Phase~A step~5 main is the definition of $\toModuleKSheaf C$ from a scheme $C$ over $\Spec k$ — a typeclass-and-construction step expressing $\struct C$ as a sheaf of $k$-modules via the structure morphism. This chapter is purely the typeclass plumbing that makes the eventual $\toModuleKSheaf$-then-$\Ext.\mathtt{instModule}$ chain reach the goal.

